{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584184"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:40:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:40:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14425"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14425","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14425"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.02,0.02,0.07,0.74]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7120"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55340"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7120","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7120"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14425"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40870"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"29"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4906"},{"type":"tags","id":"4907"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7653"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17008"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17165"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55340","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55340"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man presents to the emergency department with severe chest pain. Investigations reveal that he has suffered a myocardial infarction. Over the following days, the affected cardiac tissue undergoes a specific type of cell death.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following types of necrosis is most likely to occur in the infarcted myocardial tissue?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Liquefactive necrosis","Gangrenous necrosis","Caseous necrosis","Fibrinoid necrosis","Coagulative necrosis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Ecoagulative necrosis\u003C/strong\u003E. In myocardial infarction, the death of cardiac muscle tissue typically results in coagulative necrosis. This type of necrosis is characterised by the preservation of the basic tissue architecture for several days, allowing recognition of cell outlines.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiquefactive necrosis\u003C/strong\u003E is typically seen in infections or in the brain, where tissue liquefies due to the action of hydrolytic enzymes. It is not characteristic of myocardial infarction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGangrenous necrosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a combination of coagulative and liquefactive necrosis, often seen in the extremities due to vascular compromise. It is not typical in cardiac tissue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECaseous necrosis\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with tuberculosis and other granulomatous diseases. It appears as a cheese-like, amorphous material and is not seen in myocardial infarction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibrinoid necrosis\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in immune-mediated vascular damage and hypertension. It is characterised by the accumulation of fibrin-like proteins in vessel walls and is not typical of myocardial infarction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECoagulative necrosis in myocardial infarction occurs due to hypoxia, which leads to the denaturation of intracellular proteins. This process preserves the general structure of the tissue for a period of time before inflammatory cells arrive to remove the dead tissue.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Myocardial infarction results in coagulative necrosis 